======================================================================
PART 2: EULER CHARACTERISTIC AND f-VECTOR
======================================================================

The independence complex Δ(CG(T)) is a simplicial complex:
  f₋₁ = 1 (empty set)
  f₀ = α₁ (vertices = odd cycles)
  f₁ = α₂ (edges = disjoint pairs)
  f₂ = α₃ (triangles = disjoint triples)
  f₃ = α₄ (tetrahedra = disjoint quadruples)

The Euler characteristic:
  χ(Δ) = f₋₁ - f₀ + f₁ - f₂ + ...
       = 1 - α₁ + α₂ - α₃ + ...
       = I(-1)

If Δ is contractible: χ = 1
If Δ is a sphere S^d: χ = 1 + (-1)^d
  S⁰: χ=2, S¹: χ=0, S²: χ=2, S³: χ=0

For tournaments: I(-1) ≤ 1 (conjectured).
This means χ(Δ) ≤ 1, ruling out even-dimensional spheres.
The complex is either contractible (χ=1) or has
'more odd-dimensional holes than even' (χ < 1).

======================================================================
PART 3: f-VECTOR DISTRIBUTION AT n=9
======================================================================

n=9 (3-cycle only, 500 samples):
  Average f-vector: (1, 21.1, 53.0, 4.4)
  Average χ = 1 - 21.1 + 53.0 - 4.4 = 28.4

h-vector computation:
  h₀ = f₋₁ = 1
  h₁ = f₀ - (d+1)·f₋₁ = α₁ - (d+1) where d = max dim

h-vector for some specific tournaments at n=9:
  T0: f=(24,76,7), d=2, h=(1,21,31,-46), χ=46
  T1: f=(19,36,1), d=2, h=(1,16,1,-17), χ=17
