======================================================================
PART 4: THE DEHN-SOMMERVILLE CONSTRAINT
======================================================================

For a SIMPLICIAL SPHERE of dimension d:
  h_k = h_{d+1-k} (palindrome)

For our independence complexes, if they were spheres:
  d=2 sphere: h₀=h₃, h₁=h₂
  This gives: h₃ = 1, h₂ = h₁ = a1-3
  Then: a3 = h₃ + a2 - a1 + 1 = 1 + a2 - a1 + 1 = a2 - a1 + 2
  So χ = 1 - a1 + a2 - (a2-a1+2) = 1 - 2 = -1 ≠ 2 = χ(S²)
  CONTRADICTION! The complex is NOT a sphere.

This makes sense: CG(T) independence complexes are generally NOT spheres.
They are more like BALLS (contractible, χ=1) or have torsion.

WHEN is χ = 1 (contractible)?
